  "prompt": "Which is stronger acid, HClO4 or HIO4? And why?",
  "response": "To determine which acid is stronger between HClO4 (perchloric acid) and HIO4 (periodic acid), we need to consider the electronegativity of the central atoms and the structure of the molecules.\n\n1. **Electronegativity of Central Atoms:**\n   - Chlorine (Cl) has an electronegativity of approximately 3.16.\n   - Iodine (I) has an electronegativity of approximately 2.5.\n\n2. **Oxidation State:**\n   - In both HClO4 and HIO4, the central atoms (Cl and I) are in their highest oxidation states (+7).\n\n3. **Acid Strength and Electronegativity:**\n   - The strength of oxyacids (like HClO4 and HIO4) increases with the electronegativity of the central atom. This is because a more electronegative central atom can pull electron density away from the O-H bond more effectively, making it easier to donate a proton (H+).\n\nGiven these points, we can conclude that:\n\n- **HClO4 is a stronger acid than HIO4** because chlorine is more electronegative than iodine. The higher electronegativity of chlorine in HClO4 results in a greater polarization of the O-H bond, making it easier for HClO4 to donate a proton compared to HIO4.\n\nIn summary, due to the higher electronegativity of chlorine compared to iodine, perchloric acid (HClO4) is a stronger acid than periodic acid (HIO4).",
